<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-853-294  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 853 294.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Nov 6 1989 v23 n45 p83(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Time to open US doors to world's IS talent. (TakingCharge)(foreign-born computer professionals) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Shusterman, Carl.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The United States should re-evaluate its immigration policy in thelight of the fact that 36 percent of all computer science graduatestudents and 42 percent of all engineering graduate students in UScolleges are foreign-born.andP;  A recent Labor Department study warnsof impending labor shortages in technological professions.andP;  Manyfirms are recruiting qualified programmers and analysts fromoverseas.andP;  The proposed Immigration Act of 1989 provides for anincrease in the number of foreign professionals allowed to enterthe US each year but would make it more difficult for them toqualify for US residency and would exclude many who lack advanceddegrees.andP;  A more effective policy would increase the number ofprofessionals allowed to obtain immigrant visas to 120,000annually, avoid basing qualifications on college degrees alone andeliminate labor certification requirements in shortageoccupations.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Foreign CompetitionComputer industryMISPersonnel ManagementRecruitment.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>